# React Accessibility-First UI

When creating or changing user-facing UI, accessibility is part of the feature, not a follow-up polish pass.

## Rules

- Prefer semantic HTML and platform-native controls: `button`, `a`, `input`, `label`, `fieldset`, `legend`, headings, lists, tables, `Pressable`, `TextInput`, and equivalent native primitives.
- Do not create clickable `div`/`span` controls when a native element or accessible primitive is available.
- Every interactive control needs an accessible name:
  - visible label where practical,
  - `aria-label` / `aria-labelledby` for web icon-only controls,
  - `accessibilityLabel` / `accessibilityRole` for native controls.
- Keyboard users must be able to reach and operate web UI flows. Preserve visible focus and avoid keyboard traps.
- Dialogs, popovers, menus, and drawers must manage focus intentionally: focus enters, escape/close behavior is clear, and focus returns when appropriate.
- Form errors must be perceivable and associated with fields (`aria-describedby`, summaries, live regions, or native equivalents).
- Do not rely on color alone for meaning. Preserve contrast and respect reduced-motion preferences.
- Prefer role/label-based test locators for user flows. Use `data-testid` for workflow-critical custom widgets only when semantic locators are unstable.
- If the project has accessibility docs or E2E/axe coverage, update or run the relevant checks for changed flows.

## Framework and UI-library adapters

For cross-platform UI libraries, use project-approved wrapper primitives when raw library components leak platform-specific props or semantics. Do not bypass wrappers in shared UI packages unless the project docs explicitly allow it.

## Anti-patterns

- clickable non-interactive elements with only `onClick`
- icon-only buttons without names
- hiding focus outlines without a replacement
- introducing a modal that traps keyboard or screen-reader users
- skipping accessibility checks because the visual UI looks correct
